<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-19T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="1080" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1080">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.741/22a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-19T14:00:00-05:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">August 19, 1914, 2 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Please inquire of the Foreign Office whether the German Government has
                            itself any connection, direct or indirect, with the radio station at
                            Sayville, Long Island, now operated by a corporation known as the
                            Atlantic Communication Company, or with the radio station at Tuckerton,
                            New Jersey, built by the Hoch Frequenz Maschinen Actiengesellschaft für
                            Drahtlose Telegraphic. We feel bound in fairness to the German
                            Government to make these inquiries for our guidance in performing our
                            obligations under the third article of the Hague convention of 1907.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>